{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2dcfce11-af3c-49e9-bc85-bb9d50f61f40","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .NET crash dump. Note that the available skills here cover **collecting** dumps but not **analyzing** them, so let me provide direct guidance.\n\n**Tools for analyzing `.dmp` files:**\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze <path-to-dump>`** — cross-platform CLI tool (install via `dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump`)\n2. **WinDbg** (Windows) — with the SOS extension\n3. **lldb** (Linux/macOS) — with the SOS plugin\n\n**Key commands inside `dotnet-dump analyze`:**\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` (or `printexception`) | Show the last exception |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `clrstack` | Show managed call stack for current thread |\n| `clrstack -all` | Show stacks for all threads |\n| `dso` (or `dumpstackobjects`) | Show objects on the stack |\n| `gcroot <addr>` | Trace what's keeping an object alive |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM crashes) |\n\n**Suggested workflow:**\n1. `dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp`\n2. Run `pe` to check for an unhandled exception\n3. Run `threads` → `setthread <id>` → `clrstack` to inspect thread stacks\n4. Look for the faulting thread (often thread 0 or one marked with an exception)\n\nWould you like me to install `dotnet-dump` and walk through the analysis with you? If so, let me know the path to your `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c75c8334-c466-407b-9deb-524bc568bba2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET app and wants to analyze it. Let me think about what tools and approaches are available.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see:\n- `dump-collect` - but this is for **collecting** crash dumps, NOT analyzing them. The description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\"\n\nSo none of the available skills are directly applicable for dump **analysis**.\n\nLet me provide guidance on how to analyze a .NET crash dump. The main tools for this are:\n\n1. **dotnet-dump analyze** - cross-platform CLI tool for analyzing .NET dumps\n\n\n2. **WinDbg** (Windows) - with SOS debugging extension\n3. **lldb** (Linux/macOS) - with SOS plugin\n\nSince we're on Linux, `dotnet-dump analyze` or `lldb` with SOS would be the appropriate tools. I should ask for the dump file path and provide practical steps for analyzing it.","outputTokens":719,"requestId":"6082:1230E4:2F87CD:3E0EBB:69FFE576"},"id":"593ba9c3-6ceb-4718-b2db-82e701ae3e17","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:55:19.731Z","parentId":"05e91a81-bced-43be-903f-da14fbba7fb8"}
